review_blob: Bottle, 5.0%. Good malty aroma, dust, earth and dark roasted malts. Clear light brown colour. Small stable white head. The flavour has more dust and a vinous touch as well as the aforementioned malty notes. A little watery, but almost acceptable for the ABV. Distinct bitterness in the finish, bordering on astringent.

Bottle, 9.5%. Weak fruity aroma, hint of ashes and hay. Smells authentic. Cloudy golden colour. Good stable creamy white head. The flavour starts off nicely sweet. Then comes a creamy, sweetish and citric note with a good white wine character. Vanilla and honey sweetness. Very flavourful and yet well-balanced.

Bottle, 5.2%. Mildly citric aroma, rustic with a bready note. Cloudy dark golden colour. Small stable frothy chalk white head. The flavour starts off quite bitter, has some orange juice, quite floral, almost perfumy. The bitterness is a little astringent. Good mouthfeel. A bit past BB date, but holds up nicely.

Bottle, 5.5%. Very caramelly aroma, teaish. Almost clear amber colour. Small frothy white head. The flavour is caramelly with a fruity note, perhaps a little banana, but by no means as distinct as in many other Hefeweizens. Low bitterness as could be expected.

Bottle, 6.0%. Mild but good caramelly aroma. Almost clear dark amber colour. Small stable off-white head. The flavour is caramelly and creamy with a hint of fruit and ashes and a refreshing citric note in the finish. Low bitterness, and good and pleasant maltiness.

Bottle, 5.6%. Weak fruity aroma. Hazy dark amber colour. Good stable off-white head, something in between fizzy and rocky. The flavour is fruity with a hint of caramel. Low to medium bitterness, a little astringent.

Bottle, 8.5%. Fruity aroma, seems slightly bretty. Clear dark brown colour. Big stable creamy brown head. The flavour starts off quite bitter, then comes a fruity note and some raw liquorice. Finishes with a mild burn as from chili. Creamy mouthfeel.
UPDATED: MAY 1, 2016
beer_name: Krenkerup Oat Malt Stout for Kvickly

review_blob: Bottle, 6.2%. Mild butter aroma, hint of soy. Clear dark brown colour. Very small light brown head. The flavour is fruity with a hint of iron in the finish. Also some coffee in the aftertaste. Low bitterness.

Bottle, 4.5%. Aroma of whiskey or something, perhaps coffee. Black colour, seems cloudy. The flavour has a mild coffee note. Not bitter coffee but quite pleasant. Low bitterness from the hops as well.
UPDATED: MAY 1, 2016

Bottle, 5.0%. Weak fruity aroma. Hazy golden colour. Small frothy white head. The flavour is fruity with a touch of floral aroma hop. Much like an English bitter. Medium bitterness. Viscous mouthfeel.

Bottle, 5.8%. Fruity aroma with a farty touch. Clear dark brown colour with a red wine to it. Small frothy off-white head. The flavour is faintly roasted but rather quickly turns malty. Good dark malts, not sweet.
Bottle. Faint vegetable aroma. Almost clear dark brown colour. Small tan head. The flavour has a pleasant grain note, malty but not sweet. Low to medium bitterness.

Bottle, 7.2%. Citric and phenolic aroma with some Belgian yeast. Cloudy dark golden colour. Big stable whitish head. The flavour is fruity with a citric touch, a lot like the aroma. Also with a mild Belgian yeast note.
UPDATED: APR 28, 2016
UPDATED: APR 28, 2016

Bottle, 7.0%. Soapy hop aroma. Cloudy light brown colour. Small stable off-white head. The flavour is also a little soapy. Tastes very Thistedy, but more like a lager than ale. There is some fruit in the finish and that is that.

Bottle, 8.0%. Roasted aroma, slightly vinous, perhaps from the rum. Black colour. Good stable light brown head. The flavour is roasted and salty with a distinct ashy note. Late salty liquorice note. It does not have a lot of rum flavour, but it does have a certain mildness that may come from the rum.
Bottle, 4.4%. Clear golden colour. Small white head. The flavour is watery and fruity. Low bitterness. I got it a little cold, just out of the fridge, but this is nearly flavourless.

Bottle, 6.0%. Ashy aroma, hint of roast barley and salt. Black colour, seems clear. Big light brown head, fairly stable. The flavour is roasted and salty with more than a touch of liquorice in the finish. Good mouthfeel. The aftertaste is ashy, not as pleasant as the flavour.

Bottle, 4.7%. Faint fruit aroma. Hazy light copper colour. Small stable white head. The flavour is slightly fruity. Has a faint hint of something, not herbal but perhaps a little peppery. Mild and not very interesting.

Bottle, 7.1%. Quite citric hop aroma, also teaish. Almost clear amber colour. Big stable creamy off-white head. The flavour starts off with a quite strong bitterness, not entirely pleasant. Then comes a fruity note and more bitterness. On the whole not too bad, but could have had other hop characteristics than mostly bitterness.
UPDATED: APR 2, 2016
beer_name: gir / Beavertown Bver Double White IPA

review_blob: Bottle at K15. Bready aroma. Clear dark golden colour. Small stable white head. The flavour has an unpleasant bitterness. Standard nealko.
Draught at K15. Cloudy golden colour. Small stable head. Good hop bite in the flavour with a refreshing hoppiness. Does not have much alcohol flavour considering its ABV. But tastes good.
UPDATED: MAR 29, 2016
Bag in box at K15. Good apple aroma. Clear pale golden colour. Dry flavour. Good apple note. Dry finish, like aspartame, but not quite as bad.
Bottle, 5.4%. Malty wheat beer aroma. Cloudy amber colour. Small stable off-white head. OK malty caramelly flavour. Low bitterness. Clean finish.

Bottle, 13.6%. Aroma of paint thinner and phenols. Black colour. Small stable brown head. The flavour starts off very sweet. Extremely sugary. So. Sweet. It must be the sweetest beer I have ever had. So sweet I cannot taste anything else. Does not taste 13.6% either. Anyway, does not taste bad, that much I can say.

Bottle, 10%. Faint fruity aroma. Almost black colour. Small off-white head. The flavour is roasted and fruity with a good alcohol note in the finish to balance. The bitterness is a bit rough, perhaps too much bitterness from the alcohol. The barrelled version I liked a lot better, perhaps this would improve with a few more years in the bottle.

Bottle, 7.5%. Good blueberry aroma. Black colour. Small stable brown head. The flavour starts off with a good blueberry note and then comes a more of a standard stout flavour with the creamy and roasted notes that are expected of this style. Has a very slight perfumy note in the finish, but all in all an interesting beer, and not bad.

Can, 8%. Grapefruity aroma. Cloudy orange colour. Small stable white head. The flavour starts off quite bitter but there is also a fruity and papery note in there. High bitterness, I would actually have liked a bit more sweetness to balance it. Very good creamy mouthfeel.

Bottle, 17.5%. Surprisingly little aroma for its ABV... weak alcohol note, I guess. Black colour. No head. The flavour is roasted and creamy with a rough bitterness and some liquorice. Lots of alcohol bitterness. Sweetish, creamy and vinous, I guess, but it is hard to taste much apart from alcohol bitterness. I must admit, I do not like these kind of overly alcoholic imperial stout.
beer_name: Lervig / Evil Twin Big Ass Money Stout

review_blob: Bottle, 6.5%. Spicy brown sugar aroma, slightly roasted. Dark brown colour with a red shine. Small stable off-white head. The flavour is sweet and sugary with a hint of metal. Even a little red berry to it. Creamy finish. Low bitterness.

Bottle, 7.9%. Sourish yoghurt aroma. Cloudy yellow colour. Small white head. The flavour is fruity and spicy, has a strange papery note. Citric and alcoholic finish. Sticks in too many directions and is not very clean, I think.

Bottle, 6.5%. Citric and spicy yeast aroma. Hazy golden colour. Small stable white head. The flavour is nicely yeasty, has some fresh baking yeast or fresh-baked bread, with a hint of coriander and a mild citric note. Not the most flavourful beer I have had, but it is certainly well-balanced.

Bottle, 6.0%. OK spicy aroma, some yeast. Hazy brown colour. Big stable plasticky off-white head. The flavour is roasted and quite spicy. High carbonation. Roasted and bready flavour with some Christmas spices. Not bad.
Can, 5%. Clear golden colour. OK plasticky white head. The flavour is bready and slightly oxidised. Low bitterness. Rubber finish.

Bottle, 8.8%. Quite citric aroma, and also quite funky. Hazy golden colour. Big stable white head. The flavour is sweetish and citric with a faint hint of marazipan and phenols. Spicy notes, coriander or whatever. A bit strange and not very tripel-y, but refreshing and works well enough for me.

Bottle. Citric mango hop aroma. Cloudy greyish golden colour. Small white head. The flavour is also citric with a mild creamy white wine note. White grapes without the sugar, I guess. Low to medium bitterness. Clean but with a sweetish finish. Does not taste much of saison, but it is nice enough.

Can, 4.2%. Aroma of fresh bread. Clear pale yellow colour. OK stable creamy white head. The flavour is bready but clean. Has a low bitterness and a hint of floral hop. Some dust or cream in the finish. Could have been a lot worse.

Bottle, 7.8%. Weak creamy aroma. Black colour. Very big stable creamy brown head. The flavour is roasted with a little salt liquorice and a mild hop bite. Fruity finish with a touch of lactose. Creamy mouthfeel.

Bottle, 5.9%. Fruity aroma, hint of cat piss and white wine. Clear copper colour. Small stable creamy white head. The flavour is not as good as the aroma, meaty, Belgian yeast, strange fruit. Citric finish, slightly unclean.

Bottle, 8%. Weak fruity aroma. Clear dark golden colour. Small stable white head. The flavour is citric and peppery. Has a some fruit and finishes with a little yeast. Tastes a lot like a real Belgian tripel, but not much better than most of those. Very authentic, though, and very good, actually.
Bottle, 6.5%. Malty aroma, a little crystal malt. Clear copper colour. Very small frothy white head. The flavour has a caramelly maltiness. Unclean fruitiness. Decent bitterness, but a little rough.

Bottle, 6.0%. Salty, roasted and slightly smokey aroma. Black colour. Small stable light brown head. The flavour is salty, roasted, slightly citric, creamy, smokey. Light to medium mouthfeel, but actually nicely silky.

Bottle, 6.9%. Mild malty and bready aroma. Almost clear copper colour. Big stable creamy white head. The flavour is malty and vinous, seems a little oxidized. Mild booziness, quite nice as well. Tastes nicely Polish. But I know some canned Polish beers that are a cheaper if I want more mocne.
beer_name: Amager / Against The Grain Pocketful of Dollars

review_blob: Bottle, 5.5%. The aroma has a sort of vanilla that seems to come from the hops used, also soft fruit and perhaps dust. Cloudy dark golden colour. Good stable white head. The flavour starts off rather perfumy, has a distinct coconut and/or vanilla note. It goes away rather quickly, and then comes a distinct bitterness. Thin mouthfeel considering the style.

Bottle, 6.8%. Very fruity aroma, overripe plums, Ribena, Rynkeby rd saft. Cloudy amber colour. Big stable creamy white head. The flavour is citric and sweet. Reminds me of Flanders Red. A little funky but not really in a way I like too much. Strange.
